( { Hello everyone and welcome to Part 2 of my Lifetime Repertoire series on the Nimzo-Indian and the Queen's Indian Defenses!    Part 2 will complete your repertoire against }1.d4 { and will be centered around the Queen's Indian Defense and meeting   }3.g3 { with }3...c5 { , inviting White into the Fianchetto Benoni. In this course, you will also learn how to deal with other  1.d4  setups, such as the London, Colle, and Torre Attack.    For those of you who don't know me, I am Benjamin Bok, a Dutch Grandmaster rated over 2600 and part of the Dutch national team. This is my second course for Chessable, and I am thankful for the positive feedback I have received on Part 1 of my Lifetime Repertoire series.    When creating this course, my aim was not only to provide you with a repertoire that is solid and reliable but also one that offers Black plenty of chances to fight for the win. } )1. d4
1. Nf6( { Developing the knight and preventing White from placing a second pawn in the center with }2.e4 { , as now we would be able to take the pawn with }2...Nxe4 { . } )( { When the first principles of chess were developed, it was thought that Black's best way of preventing White from placing a second pawn in the center with  2.e4  was to place a pawn in the center themselves with }1...d5 { .    In the early 1900s, a modern approach was developed, in which Black fights for the center by controlling key squares with their pieces instead of controlling those squares with pawns. The Nimzo-Indian and Queen's Indian Defenses are among those modern openings. } )
2. c4{ White is aiming to play  3.Nc3  followed by  4.e4 , after which White would have a great center. }( { In case White continues with }2.Nf3 { we will proceed with }2...e6 { so that we can transpose to the Queen's Indian after }3.c4 b6 { .    Besides }3.c4 { , White also has various other options: }3.Bf4 { , leading to the London System; }3.Bg5 { , leading to the Torre Attack; }3.e3 { , leading to the Colle System; }3.g3 { , which will be quite similar to the  Declined Benoni . } )
2. e6( { Opening up the  f8 - a3  diagonal for our bishop, so we can meet }3.Nc3 { with }3...Bb4 { . } )
3. Nf3( { White delays the development of the  b1 -knight and develops the other knight. }3...Bb4+ { is still possible, and leads to the Bogo-Indian Defense, but it has lost its punch somewhat, as White can meet this move with }4.Bd2 { or }4.Nbd2 { and one of the key ideas in the Nimzo-Indian is often to trade }{ on  c3  and give White doubled c-pawns. } )( { ➢ With }3.g3 { , White avoids the Queen's Indian and aims to play the Catalan. However, we have no interest in going into the Catalan. }3...c5 { , }{ inviting White into the Fianchetto Benoni. Generally, I do not recommend the Benoni, but the Fianchetto Variation is one of the few systems against which Black is completely fine. Besides, the sharp nature of the Benoni also gives Black plenty of chances to fight for the win. }( 3...b6?! { no longer makes sense, as here White plays }4.Bg2 { and immediately attacks the rook on  a8 , forcing us to make an awkward move to address White's threat. } )4.d5 { , }{ White's most principled move, gaining more space and accepting the invitation into the Fianchetto Benoni. }( { White can also play }4.Nf3 { , }{ leading to the Benoni Declined. } ) )( { ➢ We will meet }3.Nc3 { with }3...Bb4 { , }{ which leads to the Nimzo-Indian presented in Part 1. } )
3. b6{ This move marks the beginning of the Queen's Indian Defense. The Queen's Indian is the sister opening of the Nimzo-Indian, as we continue aiming to control central squares with our pieces instead of pawns. Furthermore, we can still meet a potential  Nc3  with ... Bb4 , leading to positions that are similar to the Nimzo. }
4. g3( { White's most popular move and also the critical test of the Queen's Indian. White aims to develop the bishop to  g2  and castle kingside afterwards. Besides }4.g3 { , White also has other options, the most popular ones being }4.a3 { and }4.Nc3 { . } )
4. Ba6{ Against any other fourth move from White, we will develop our bishop to  b7 , but here we will play this move, attacking the  c4 -pawn, and thus forcing White to protect it somehow. White has many ways to do so, and they all have their pros and cons. In the different chapters, you will learn how to deal with all of White's continuations. }
