1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3( { White's main move to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense. Here, }3...Bb4+ { has somewhat lost its punch, as White has the more suitable responses }4.Bd2 { and }4.Nbd2 { . } )
3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. g3{ The critical test of the Queen's Indian. White aims to fianchetto the light-squared bishop as well and delays  Nc3 , as we can often meet that with ... Bb4 , after which we have the positional threat of ... Bxc3 . }
4. Ba6( { Against almost any other 4th move, we play }4...Bb7 { , }{ but here this is our right continuation, as we develop the bishop with tempo and force White to defend the  c4 -pawn with a slightly awkward move. } )
5. Qc2{ The most dangerous line against  4...Ba6  in the Queen's Indian. It involves a pawn sacrifice that rose in popularity in the late 2000s and early 2010s. Black was under pressure for a while in this variation, but the experts in this opening have figured out how to neutralize White's initiative. }
5. c5{ The most accurate move order. We want to challenge White's center as quickly as possible. }( { Following }5...Bb7 6.Bg2 c5 { , White has real chances for an advantage after }7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.O-O { , as }{ the  b1 -knight can comfortably develop to the  c3 -square since there is no pressure on the  c4 -pawn. } )
6. d5{ White's most critical continuation and the start of the aforementioned pawn sacrifice. }
6. exd5
7. cxd5
7. Bb7( { Further attacking the  d5 -pawn, as we are getting ready to take it on our next move. Of course not }7...Nxd5? { , as this allows the double attack }8.Qe4+ { , and White gets a decisive material advantage. } )
8. Bg2{ White does not have a good way to defend the  d5 -pawn so their best bet is just to continue development. }
8. Nxd5{ Finally, we do take the  d5 -pawn. }
9. Qb3{ With this move, White is aiming for a very direct approach with  Ne5  coming quickly. }
9. Nc7
10. Ne5{ Threatening checkmate on  f7  and attacking the bishop on  b7  at the same time. Fortunately, we can parry both threats. }
10. d5
11. Nc3{ White needs to follow up energetically, as otherwise, they are just down a pawn for insufficient compensation. }
11. Be7{ We should just continue our development and aim to castle on the next move. }
12. Bf4{ White continues development and is aiming to follow up with  Rd1  or  O-O-O , to increase the pressure on our  d5 -pawn. }
12. O-O
13. O-O-O
13. c4( { I recommend this move, as I believe it offers the easiest path to equality. }13...Nc6 { is also fine. } )
14. Nxc4{ White's only move to maintain the balance, as otherwise, they are just down a pawn for insufficient compensation. The following line is forced. }
14. dxc4
15. Rxd8
15. Bxd8( { Of course not }15...cxb3? 16.Rxf8+ Kxf8 17.Bxb7 { , when White is winning material and the game. } )
16. Bxb7{ White has to give back the queen, as otherwise, we simply get too much material. }( 16.Qxc4?! { is quite risky, as after }16...Bxg2 { , we get more than enough material in return for White's queen. More details are given in the  corresponding chapter . } )
16. cxb3
17. Bxc7
17. bxa2
18. Nxa2
18. Bxc7{ We get equal chances in this endgame because of the opposite-colored bishops. }
