8. Bg2{ White does not have a good way to defend the  d5 -pawn so their best bet is just to continue development. }
8. Nxd5{ Finally, we do take the  d5 -pawn. }
9. O-O{ Perhaps somewhat surprisingly, White just continues development and does not go for a direct attack to compensate for the pawn. White's compensation is based on the fact that they have long-term pressure along the d-file, and that it is not so easy for Black to complete development. That being said, we are up a pawn, and if we manage to consolidate, we will get winning chances as well. }
9. Nc6{ The most accurate move order, as this limits White's options the most. }( 9...Be7 { has been Black's most popular choice, but I believe the text is slightly more accurate.  9...Be7  gives White the additional option of }10.Qe4 { , which is a tricky line that I suggest we avoid. } )
10. Rd1{ White's usual follow-up, bringing the rook into the game, attacking the knight on  d5 , and exerting pressure on the d-file. }( { Now }10.Qe4+ { can be met with }10...Nde7 { , which is the only proper way to deal with White's double attack. }{ We are aiming to play ... d5  quickly, and I'd suggest going through the  variations  for further details, but Black gets a fine game in all cases. } )
10. Be7{ Instead of moving or defending the knight on  d5 , we defend it with tactical means. }
11. a3{ Taking away the  b4 -square from the knight and thus reintroducing the threat of  Rxd5 . As a result, Black is forced to retreat the knight from  d5 .     This move was played three times in 2011 by Cheparinov and initially put Black under a lot of pressure. However, with accurate play, we have nothing to worry about. }( { White shouldn't take the knight: }11.Rxd5? Nb4 { , }{ forking the rook on  d5  and the queen on  c2 . }12.Qd1 Bxd5 { . Instead, after }12...Nxd5? { White wins material with }13.Ne1+- { . The variation is  analyzed  in more depth in the appropriate chapter. } )
11. Nc7( { The right retreating move. After }11...Nf6?! 12.e4 { , White gets a dangerous initiative. We should avoid this line. } )
12. Nc3( { White just continues development. }12.Bf4 Ne6 13.e3 O-O 14.Nc3 { transposes to the main line. } )
12. O-O{ We should continue our development as well. }
13. Bf4{ The most active developing square for White's bishop. }
13. Ne6{ We are aiming to trade our knight for White's bishop on  f4 , as we want to play ... d6  eventually. Without White's dark-squared bishop, there won't be too much pressure on our  d6 -pawn. }
14. e3{ White aims to recapture on  f4  with the e-pawn. }
14. Nxf4
15. exf4( { White can still choose to recapture on  f4  with }15.gxf4 { , but our plan will remain the same. }15...d6 16.Rd2 Qd7 { , and this position is quite  similar  to the one that arises after  14.Rd2 . } )
15. d6{ First, we should relieve the pressure on the d-pawn a bit by putting it on a protected square. }
16. Rd2{ White aims to double the rooks to exert more pressure on our d-pawn. }
16. h6{ We should play this move, to make sure that White has no annoying  Ng5  jumps. }
17. Rad1
17. Re8{ And now we make this small improving move. White can start complicating matters, but we are ready for it. }
18. Ne5{ White's most testing move, using the pin on the d-file to attack our knight on  c6 , and also eyeing the  f7 -pawn. }
18. Nd4{ Our only move to maintain the balance. We cannot passively defend the knight on  c6 , as White would often have the  Nxf7  sacrifice. }
19. Rxd4
19. Bxg2
20. R4d2( { White should move their rook, as it's under attack. }20.R4d3 Bh3 21.Nb5 Qc8 22.Nxd6 Bxd6 23.Rxd6 { transposes to the  main line . } )
20. Bh3( { The best square for our bishop. Now }21.Qb3 { can be met by }21...Be6 { . For more details, see the  relevant section . } )( { Note that }20...Bb7 { is slightly inaccurate due to }21.Qb3 Rf8 22.Nb5↑ { and White has some initiative. } )
