1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3( { White's main move to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense. Here, }3...Bb4+ { has somewhat lost its punch, as White has the more suitable responses }4.Bd2 { and }4.Nbd2 { . } )
3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. Bf4{ A bit of a sideline that has been played by some strong players, such as Andreikin and Duda. White brings out the dark-squared bishop to an active square and delays the development of the  b1 -knight. }
4. Bb7{ We will play this move against anything other than  4.g3 . We develop our bishop to this active square and keep our options open as to how we want to challenge White's center. }
5. e3( { White continues development. }5.a3 { transposes to the  4.a3 variation . } )
5. Bb4+{ We develop our bishop to this square anyway, as it is not that easy for White to deal with this check. }
6. Nfd2{ An odd-looking move. White's idea is to push our dark-squared bishop back with a potential  a3 , so they can develop the  b1 -knight to  c3  afterwards, without giving us the opportunity to damage their pawn structure. }( 6.Nc3 { transposes to the  4.Nc3 line . } )
6. c5{ We challenge White's pawn center right away. }
7. a3{ White challenges our bishop on  b4 , giving us no choice but to trade it for White's knight on  d2 . }
7. Bxd2+
8. Qxd2{ White recaptures with the queen so they can recapture with the queen on  d4  and develop the knight to  c3 . }
8. cxd4{ If White gets the time to consolidate, their bishop pair will give them an advantage, so we should try to open up the center as quickly as possible. }
9. Qxd4
9. Nc6{ Developing our knight and attacking White's queen on  d4 . }
10. Qd1{ White drops the queen all the way back. }
10. d5{ Since White is underdeveloped, we want to break in the center as quickly as possible. }
11. Nc3{ White's only move to maintain the balance. White develops another piece and maintains the tension in the center. }
11. d4{ This central break allows us to further activate our knight and bishop. }
12. exd4{ White has no choice but to trade. }
12. Nxd4{ Black has a fine game here, as we have active piece play, and it will not be that easy for White to complete their development. }
