7. Nb3{ This line is actually quite tricky and has been played by numerous top players recently, including Magnus Carlsen against Ding Liren. }( 7.Nf3 Nc6 8.c4 d4 { would also transpose to the  Benoni Declined  chapter. } )
7. Be6{ This is the right way to continue our development. We are going to delay ... Nc6 , as we want to be able to meet  Bg5  with ... Nbd7 . }( { The natural-looking }7...Nc6 { would be inaccurate, as here White has }8.Bg5 Be6 9.Nc3 { , with nagging pressure on our center. } )
8. Nc3
8. Be7
9. f4{ White's best approach to exert pressure on Black's center. White is not only threatening to play  fxe5  but also  f5  to kick the bishop away. }
9. exf4
10. gxf4{ The critical continuation. White still wants to play  f5  to kick the bishop away so that the  d5 -pawn becomes weak. }( { After }10.Bxf4 { , we will just play }10...O-O= { followed }{ by ... Nc6  and Black has nothing to worry about. } )
10. g6{ Stopping the  f5  push. }
11. Nd4{ If White wants to get the bishop pair, they should play this move now. Otherwise, we will play ... Nc6  and we will always be able to trade on  d4 . }
11. Nc6{ The best continuation is just to give up the bishop pair and continue our development. }
12. Nxe6
12. fxe6{ After some complications in the opening, we finally landed in this position. White has the bishop pair and the pawn on  e6  can become a target. In exchange, we have comfortable piece play. White can often try to play  e4  to open up the position for the bishops, but we will always have a good way to respond to that. }
13. Kh1
13. O-O{ White may have the bishop pair, but our pieces are nicely coordinated. Furthermore, White is struggling to find a comfortable square for the dark-squared bishop. }( { Ding played }13...Kf7 { , but after }14.e4 dxe4 15.Nxe4 Nxe4 16.Bxe4⩲ { , White was slightly better, as the bishops have become more active now. Carlsen-Ding Liren, chess24.com 2022. } )
14. Qd3{ This was played by Svane against Praggnanandhaa in the 2022 Chennai Olympiad. White's idea is to play  Qh3  quickly to exert pressure on our  e6 -pawn. Moreover, this move further prepares  e4 . }
14. Bb4{ The most precise. With this move, we make it more difficult for White to get  e4  in, as we will often just trade our bishop for White's knight on  c3  to get more control of the central squares. Black has a fine game here, and we will also get our chance to take over the initiative. }
