[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "London System 3.Bf4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. e6{ We have to play this move to be able to transpose to the Queen's Indian. }
3. Bf4
3. c5( 3...d5 { is also fine, as after }4.e3 c5 { , we transpose. } )
4. e3
4. d5{ I recommend this system, as it keeps things very simple and White will never be able to catch us off guard by capturing the pawn on  c5 . Generally, we will follow up with ... Bd6  and ask White how they are going to deal with the offered bishop trade.    Note that we are delaying ... Nc6 , as in some cases we want to be able to go ... Qc7  followed by ... Nbd7 , to prepare the ... e5  break. White has many different move orders, and often they transpose to the same positions. }
5. c3
5. Bd6
6. Bg3{ The most played move by a large margin, so you will most likely have to face this. }
6. O-O
7. Nbd2
7. Qc7
8. dxc5{ This is Le Quang Liem's suggestion in his London course. }( { If White still wants to place the knight on  e5 , they should do it now with }8.Ne5 { , as otherwise, we will prevent them from doing so with  8...Nbd7 . However, after }8...b6 { followed }{ by ... Ba6 , Black is doing absolutely fine. } )
8. Qxc5
9. Bd3
9. Nbd7{ Again, we are developing the knight to the  d7 -square to make sure that our queen can always keep protecting the bishop on  d6 . Furthermore, the knight protects the knight on  f6 , which is quite useful in some variations, and after a subsequent ... b6  and ... Bb7 , our knight will not be blocking the bishop. }
10. Qe2
10. h6{ Liem does not cover this point. The idea is to make sure that the pawn on  h7  will never be hanging after a subsequent ... Bxg3   hxg3 . Furthermore, we delay ... Bxg3 , as then White has the additional option of  Rh4  followed by a quick  g4 - g5 . }( 10...Bxg3 11.hxg3 h6 12.Rh4!? { is what we want to avoid. } )
11. e4
11. Bxg3
12. hxg3
12. dxe4
13. Nxe4
13. Nxe4
14. Qxe4
14. Nf6
15. Qe5
15. Qb6{ Trading on  e5  would give White a slightly better endgame, so we should play this clever move instead. The threat to the  b2 -pawn is somewhat awkward to deal with, and we will continue to develop our pieces in the next couple of moves. }
