[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Colle System 3.e3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. e6{ We have to play this move to be able to transpose to the Queen's Indian. }
3. e3{ The Colle System. White aims to develop the light-squared bishop to  d3  and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with a subsequent  b3  and  Bb2 . Furthermore, White is delaying the move  c4  and the development of their  b1 -knight, so they can later choose whether they want to continue with  c4  and  Nc3  or develop the knight to  d2 . }
3. b6{ We will stick to our guns and again go for a Queen's Indian setup. }
4. Bd3{ White sticks to their plan and develops the light-squared bishop. }
4. Bb7
5. O-O( { White continues development and keeps their options open as to how they want to develop the queenside. }5.c4 { transposes to the  4.c4 variation . } )
5. d5{ Eventually, we should place a pawn in the center ourselves. We can continue from here by exerting pressure on White's center with ... c5 , but also by going for a setup with ... Bd6  and ... Nbd7 . }
6. b3{ With this move, White prepares to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. Furthermore, in the event of a potential  c4   dxc4 , White is now able to recapture with the b-pawn. }
6. c5{ After some careful consideration, I have decided on this to aim for a setup with ... Nc6  and ... Bd6 , as it is the most active. }
7. Bb2{ White sticks to their plan and fianchettoes the dark-squared bishop. }
7. Nc6{ As I said before, I like this move best, as it is the most active square for our knight. }
8. Nbd2{ White continues with this typical developing move. }
8. Bd6{ I like this move, as our bishop is most active here. White has plenty of options to choose from as to how they want to continue, but Black is doing fine after all of them. }
9. dxc5{ White aims to clarify the situation in the center somewhat and follow up with a potential  c4  or  e4 . This is also what the strong Spanish GM David Anton Guijarro played against me in an online rapid game. }
9. bxc5{ The right recapture and deviating from the aforementioned game. I prefer this recapture, as it gives us more control in the center. }
10. c4{ White challenges our center and aims to give us hanging pawns by trading on  d5  in the foreseeable future. }
10. O-O{ Black has a fine game here, as we have an active piece setup. We can continue improving our position with moves like ... Re8  and ... h6 . Furthermore, if White takes on  d5 , we aim to recapture with the e-pawn to keep our central control. }
