8. Nxd5{ Finally, we do take the  d5 -pawn. }
9. Qb3{ With this move, White is aiming for a very direct approach with  Ne5  coming quickly. }
9. Nc7
10. Ne5{ Threatening checkmate on  f7  and attacking the bishop on  b7  at the same time. Fortunately, we can parry both threats. }
10. d5
11. Nc3{ White needs to follow up energetically, as otherwise, they are just down a pawn for insufficient compensation. }
11. Be7{ We should just continue our development and aim to castle on the next move. }
12. Bf4{ White continues development and is aiming to follow up with  Rd1  or  O-O-O , to increase the pressure on our  d5 -pawn. }
12. O-O
13. Rd1
13. c4{ Here, this is our only move to maintain the balance. }
14. Qc2
14. Qc8{ Getting out of the pin on the d-file and protecting our bishop so we do not have to worry about  Nxc4  anymore. }
15. O-O{ White just continues development and refrains from taking back the pawn for now. }
15. Nba6{ Defending the pawn on  d5  indirectly. If White were to take it, we would have the fork on  b4  again at the end. }
16. e4{ White's only move to maintain the balance, increasing the pressure on our center. }( 16.Nxd5?? Nxd5 17.Bxd5 Bxd5 18.Rxd5 Nb4–+ { , }{ forking the queen on  c2  and the rook on  d5 , and Black wins. } )
16. f6{ Kicking White's knight away from  e5 . }
17. Nc6{ The only move for White to maintain the balance. White sacrifices a full knight but is actually okay in the complications. }
17. Bxc6{ Of course we should take the knight. }
18. exd5{ We now see the point behind White's sacrifice, as White is threatening both  dxc6  and  d6 , forking our bishop and knight. }
18. Bb7{ We want to keep this bishop and trade off White's bishop on  g2 . }
19. d6
19. Bxg2
20. dxe7{ A tricky continuation, but Black is absolutely fine here as well. }
20. Qh3
21. exf8=Q+
21. Rxf8{ We are currently down an exchange, but the threat of ... Bf3  is devastating, so White will need to address it. }
22. Qe2{ White's best way to defend against our aforementioned threat. }
