[Black "QID 5.Qc2 − 11.Qf5 Nf6 12.e4 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3( { White's main move to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense. Here, }3...Bb4+ { has somewhat lost its punch, as White has the more suitable responses }4.Bd2 { and }4.Nbd2 { . } )
3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. g3{ The critical test of the Queen's Indian. White aims to fianchetto the light-squared bishop as well and delays  Nc3 , as we can often meet that with ... Bb4 , after which we have the positional threat of ... Bxc3 . }
4. Ba6( { Against almost any other 4th move, we play }4...Bb7 { , }{ but here this is our right continuation, as we develop the bishop with tempo and force White to defend the  c4 -pawn with a slightly awkward move. } )
5. Qc2{ The most dangerous line against  4...Ba6  in the Queen's Indian. It involves a pawn sacrifice that rose in popularity in the late 2000s and early 2010s. Black was under pressure for a while in this variation, but the experts in this opening have figured out how to neutralize White's initiative. }
5. c5{ The most accurate move order. We want to challenge White's center as quickly as possible. }( { Following }5...Bb7 6.Bg2 c5 { , White has real chances for an advantage after }7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.O-O { , as }{ the  b1 -knight can comfortably develop to the  c3 -square since there is no pressure on the  c4 -pawn. } )
6. d5{ White's most critical continuation and the start of the aforementioned pawn sacrifice. }
6. exd5
7. cxd5
7. Bb7( { Further attacking the  d5 -pawn, as we are getting ready to take it on our next move. Of course not }7...Nxd5? { , as this allows the double attack }8.Qe4+ { , and White gets a decisive material advantage. } )
8. Bg2{ White does not have a good way to defend the  d5 -pawn so their best bet is just to continue development. }
8. Nxd5{ Finally, we do take the  d5 -pawn. }
9. O-O{ Perhaps somewhat surprisingly, White just continues development and does not go for a direct attack to compensate for the pawn. White's compensation is based on the fact that they have long-term pressure along the d-file and that it is not so easy for Black to complete development. That being said, we are up a pawn, and if we manage to consolidate, we will get winning chances as well. }
9. Nc6{ The most accurate move order, as this limits White's options the most. }( 9...Be7 { has been Black's most popular choice, but I believe the text is slightly more accurate.  9...Be7  gives White the additional option of }10.Qe4 { , which is a tricky line that I suggest we avoid. } )
10. Rd1{ White's usual follow-up, bringing the rook into the game, attacking the knight on  d5 , and exerting pressure on the d-file. }
10. Be7{ Instead of moving or defending the knight on  d5 , we defend it with tactical means. }
11. Qf5( { Besides }11.Qa4 { , this is White's second main move. }{ White moves the queen from  c2 , creating the threat of  12.Qxd5  or  12.Rxd5 , as ... Nb4  would no longer create a fork.     Furthermore, White moves the queen to the kingside, which gives chances to launch an initiative on that side of the board. This is also what Anish Giri played in the recent Tata Steel Masters against Magnus Carlsen. } )
11. Nf6{ The best square for our knight and the only move to maintain the balance. }
12. e4{ White wants to play  e5  quickly to kick our knight from  f6 . }
12. g6{ It is important to play this move first. It forces the queen to  f4 , as that is the only square where the queen protects the pawn on  e4 . }( { Instead, }12...O-O { runs into }13.e5 { , }{ when Black has an issue with both the knight on  f6  and the pawn on  d7 . } )
13. Qf4
13. O-O{ As we have no good way of stopping  e5 , we should just continue our development. }
14. e5{ White manages to achieve the desired  e5  push, and now we have to move our knight. }
14. Nh5{ The best square for our knight, as we gain a tempo on the white queen. }
15. Qg4{ The critical line of the  11.Qf5  variation. The lines get sharp and forcing here so I'd suggest to practice diligently with the move trainer in order to remember all the right moves. }
15. Qb8{ Attacking the  e5 -pawn and making sure that  Rxd7  won't come with tempo, as our queen will not be under attack. }
16. Bh6( { This move has also been played a handful of times, but it is not as testing as }16.Nc3 { . } )
16. Re8{ The best square for our rook. }
17. Nc3{ White continues development. }
17. Nxe5{ We should take the pawn, as otherwise, White's initiative will be too strong. }
18. Nxe5
18. Bxg2
19. Nxg6( { White's only move to maintain the balance. }19.Nxf7? { has been played in two games but after }19...Bc6–+ { , Black has a decisive advantage, as we have an extra pawn and a better position. } )
19. hxg6
20. Kxg2
20. Qb7+{ White certainly has compensation for the pawn but for equality at most. White will need to continue playing accurately to maintain the balance. }
