22. c4( { The only way to maintain the balance, creating the devastating threat of ... Bc5 +. After }22...Rd8 23.Rf2 { , White is slightly better. } )
23. Nd7{ White's only move not to lose the game right away, stopping our threat of ... Bc5 +. }
23. Re8{ Reinforcing the threat of ... Bc5 +, as now we would have ... Re1 # at the end. Furthermore, we also threaten ... Nxd7 , as now our bishop on  e7  is protected. }
24. Rf2{ White's only move not to lose, making sure that ... Bc5  no longer comes with check. }
24. Bc5
25. Be3{ White's only move not to lose right away. }( 25.Nxf6+?? { would not be a good idea, as after }25...Qxf6-+ { , White is lost. We are going to regain the material, and Black will be up a couple of pawns. The point is of course that }26.Qxf6 { runs into }26...Re1# { . } )
25. Bxe3
26. Nxf6+
26. Kf8
27. Qh6+( { The only move if White does not want to force a draw right away with }27.Nd7+ Kg8 28.Nf6+ Kf8= { . } )
27. Bxh6{ We have to take the queen, of course. }
28. Rxf3
28. Bxf3
29. Nxe8
29. Kxe8{ After some wild complications, we land in this endgame that is in dynamic equilibrium due to our strong bishop pair. }
