4. g3{ The critical test of the Queen's Indian. White aims to fianchetto the light-squared bishop as well and delays  Nc3 , as we can often meet that with ... Bb4 , after which we have the positional threat of ... Bxc3 . }
4. Ba6( { Against almost any other 4th move, we play }4...Bb7 { , }{ but here this is our right continuation, as we develop the bishop with tempo and force White to defend the  c4 -pawn with a slightly awkward move. } )
5. b3{ White's most popular move and arguably the critical test of the Queen's Indian. White calmly defends the pawn on  c4  and also vacates the  b2 -square for the bishop. Since our bishop on  a6  has just been shut out, we should open up its scope again with an eventual ... d5 . }
5. Bb4+{ A clever check that forces White to slightly misplace the pieces. }
6. Bd2
6. Be7{ At first glance, it may seem odd to move the bishop twice in the opening, but provoking  Bd2  is quite common in these positions, as it deprives White of the option to develop the  b1 -knight to  d2 . }
7. Nc3{ Preparing  e4 . To prevent White from doing so, we will play ... d5 . }
7. d5{ This is quite likely to transpose to the other lines. }
