8. d5{ With this move, we invite White to take on  d5 , and force us to recapture with the e-pawn, leading to a pawn structure that is characteristic of the Queen's Indian. }( { We can also prepare ... d5  by playing }8...c6 { . However, while analyzing these positions, I found that White often has a small advantage without much risk after }9.Bc3 d5 10.Ne5 { or }10.Nbd2 { . } )
9. Ne5{ A tricky move. Delaying the trade on  d5  has quite some venom to it, as here we do not have the plan of ... Re8  and ... Nf8 - e6 . Therefore, we should proceed in a different fashion. }
9. c5{ Challenging White's center right away. }
10. Bf4{ Maintaining the tension in the center and moving the bishop to a more active square, so that White can recapture on  d4  with the queen. }
10. cxd4
11. Qxd4
11. Nfd7{ It looks somewhat insane to unprotect the pawn on  d5 , but this is the right way to challenge White's knight on  e5 , as we do not allow  Nc6  and we also have ... Bf6  in many lines. }
12. cxd5{ White's only critical move. }
12. Nxe5
13. Bxe5
13. Nd7
14. Bxg7
14. e5{ Disconnecting the queen and the bishop, and the tactics work out for Black. }
15. Bxe5
15. Nxe5
16. Nc3( 16.Qxe5? Bf6–+ { and Black wins, as we are going to collect a full rook on the next move. } )
16. Bd6{ White does not have sufficient compensation for the sacrificed piece. }
