18. Rc1{ White's best move, bringing  c5  ideas in the position, which would often sacrifice a pawn, but it would also give White the  c4 -square for the knight. }
18. Ne4{ The most accurate, offering the trade of knights and making sure that White cannot get the knight to  c4 . }
19. Nxe4
19. Qxe4
20. Qa4( { This will likely lead to the same thing as after }20.Qb3 Qc6 { since }21.Qb4 { is again White's best move. } )
20. Qc6{ Offering the trade of queens and attacking the  d6 -pawn. }
21. Qb4( 21.Qa3 Nc5 { is fine for us as well, as we are going to take }{ on  d6  on the next move: }22.Nxc5 Qxd6= { and the pin makes sure White's knight cannot be saved. } )
21. a5{ Pushing the queen back a bit, as that would enable us to use a tactical idea. }
22. Qa3
22. Nc5{ Blocking the queen's defense of the  d6 -pawn, which we are going to take on the next move. }
23. Rfd1( { In case White plays }23.Nxc5 { , we will still play }23...Qxd6!= { , taking advantage of White's unprotected }{ queen on  a3 . } )
23. Qxd6{ In case White keeps the tension, we can play ... h6  on the next move to improve our position a bit. The position is dead equal and this is probably just going to be a draw. }
