4. Ba6( { Against almost any other 4th move, we play }4...Bb7 { , }{ but here this is our right continuation, as we develop the bishop with tempo and force White to defend the  c4 -pawn with a slightly awkward move. } )
5. b3{ White's most popular move and arguably the critical test of the Queen's Indian. White calmly defends the pawn on  c4  and also vacates the  b2 -square for the bishop. Since our bishop on  a6  has just been shut out, we should open up its scope again with an eventual ... d5 . }
5. Bb4+{ A clever check that forces White to slightly misplace the pieces. }
6. Bd2
6. Be7{ At first glance, it may seem odd to move the bishop twice in the opening, but provoking  Bd2  is quite common in these positions, as it deprives White of the option to develop the  b1 -knight to  d2 . }
7. Bg2
7. O-O( { It is also fine to start with }7...d5 { followed by ... O-O . } )
8. O-O
8. d5{ With this move, we invite White to take on  d5 , and force us to recapture with the e-pawn, leading to a pawn structure that is characteristic of the Queen's Indian. }( { We can also prepare ... d5  by playing }8...c6 { . However, while analyzing these positions, I found that White often has a small advantage without much risk after }9.Bc3 d5 10.Ne5 { or }10.Nbd2 { . } )
9. cxd5
9. exd5
10. Nc3( { In case of }10.Ne5 { , we will play }10...Bb7 { and White's best move is still }11.Nc3 { , which transposes to  10.Nc3 . } )
10. Re8( { The tabiya of the   }4.g3 Ba6 5.b3 { Queen's Indian. }{ White has plenty of options to choose from here. White can try to go for a quick  b3 - b4  to clamp down on the ... c5  break with the moves  a3  or  Rb1 . White can also go for more of a central strategy with  Rc1 ,  Ne5 , and  Bf4  in any order.    When White tries to carry out a quick  b4  push, we should respond in a more concrete manner. Whereas against the latter, we will generally continue with ... Bb7  and ... Nbd7 - f8 - e6 .    The appeal of these positions is that almost all of the pieces are still on the board, and there is a slight imbalance in the pawn structure. These factors combined offer us great chances to outplay our opponents, as we will be more familiar with the plans and ideas. } )
11. Ne5
11. Bb7{ We should drop the bishop back to defend the  d5 -pawn once more, so we can continue our development with ... Nbd7 . }
12. Rc1
12. Nbd7
13. Nb5{ White can also go for this direct move, attacking the  c7 -pawn. }
13. c5{ The only proper way to deal with White's threat to the  c7 -pawn. }
14. Bf4{ White activates the dark-squared bishop and is now threatening  Nxd7  followed by  Nc7 , forking both our rooks. }
14. Nf8{ Addressing the threat of  Nxd7  and starting our usual maneuver of ... Nf8 - e6 ,to exert pressure on White's bishop on  f4  and the pawn on  d4 . }
15. Nc4{ A tricky move. The knight is untouchable due to  Bxb7 , and White is threatening all sorts of forks with  Nc7  and  Nbd6 / Ncd6 . Fortunately, we have a way to disturb White's coordination. }
15. Ne6{ Exerting pressure on the important bishop on  f4  that is facilitating White's knight jumps. }
16. Nbd6{ White's only move to maintain the balance, they have to enter the complications. }
16. Nxf4
17. Nxb7{ Again, White's only move to maintain the balance. }
17. Nxe2+{ The most accurate. }
18. Qxe2
18. Qd7{ Trapping White's knight on  b7 . }
19. Nxc5( { Black would also be completely fine after }19.dxc5 Qxb7 20.cxb6 axb6= { . } )
19. Bxc5{ After the dust has settled, we end up in this symmetrical position with opposite-colored bishops where Black is fine. After White moves the queen, we will play ... Bd6  to discourage White from playing  Ne5 . }
