14. Nf8{ Our typical response to  Bf4 , rerouting the knight to  e6 . }
15. Bc1{ It might look odd to drop the bishop back to its initial square, but  b2  is actually the best square for White's dark-squared bishop, as White would like to play  e3  without having to worry that the bishop could get trapped on  f4 . Furthermore, White can now reroute the knight with  e3 ,  Ne2 - f4 . }
15. Ne6
16. Bb2
16. Bd6( 16...c6 { allows }17.e4 { . } )
17. Nb5{ White has this additional option if they want to deviate from the standard  e3 ,  Ne2 - f4  plan. }
17. Bf8{ Of course, we do not want to give up our dark-squared bishop for White's knight. }
18. e3
18. c5{ White's knight on  b5  is a bit off, and therefore, White is less equipped to deal with this push in the center. Black has a fine game here, and next, we are going to play ... a6 , and after the knight retreats to  c3 , we will take on  d4  followed by ... Rc8 . }
