5. b3{ White's most popular move and arguably the critical test of the Queen's Indian. White calmly defends the pawn on  c4  and also vacates the  b2 -square for the bishop. Since our bishop on  a6  has just been shut out, we should open up its scope again with an eventual ... d5 . }
5. Bb4+{ A clever check that forces White to slightly misplace the pieces. }
6. Bd2
6. Be7{ At first glance, it may seem odd to move the bishop twice in the opening, but provoking  Bd2  is quite common in these positions, as it deprives White of the option to develop the  b1 -knight to  d2 . }
7. Bg2
7. O-O( { It is also fine to start with }7...d5 { followed by ... O-O . } )
8. O-O
8. d5{ With this move, we invite White to take on  d5 , and force us to recapture with the e-pawn, leading to a pawn structure that is characteristic of the Queen's Indian. }( { We can also prepare ... d5  by playing }8...c6 { . However, while analyzing these positions, I found that White often has a small advantage without much risk after }9.Bc3 d5 10.Ne5 { or }10.Nbd2 { . } )
9. cxd5
9. exd5
10. Nc3( { In case of }10.Ne5 { , we will play }10...Bb7 { and White's best move is still }11.Nc3 { , which transposes to  10.Nc3 . } )
10. Re8( { The tabiya of the   }4.g3 Ba6 5.b3 { Queen's Indian. }{ White has plenty of options to choose from here. White can try to go for a quick  b3 - b4  to clamp down on the ... c5  break with the moves  a3  or  Rb1 . White can also go for more of a central strategy with  Rc1 ,  Ne5 , and  Bf4  in any order.    When White tries to carry out a quick  b4  push, we should respond in a more concrete manner. Whereas against the latter, we will generally continue with ... Bb7  and ... Nbd7 - f8 - e6 .    The appeal of these positions is that almost all of the pieces are still on the board, and there is a slight imbalance in the pawn structure. These factors combined offer us great chances to outplay our opponents, as we will be more familiar with the plans and ideas. } )
11. Rb1{ Topalov introduced this move in the 2016 Candidates Tournament against Karjakin. White's idea is to play  b4 - b5  and somewhat isolate the  d5 -pawn, as then ... c5  and ... c6  could be met with  bxc6 . }
11. Nbd7{ We will just continue our development and allow White to play  b4 . }( { Stopping White from playing  b4  with }11...c5 { is inadvisable, as after }12.dxc5 bxc5 13.Ne5 Bb7 14.Bf4 Bf8 15.Rb2⩲ { , White had serious pressure on }{ the  d5 -pawn in Topalov-Karjakin, Moscow 2016. } )
12. b4
12. Bc4{ Taking advantage of the fact that White has weakened the  c4 -square. If we are given the chance, we can further cement the bishop with ... b5 . }
13. Qc2{ With this move, White is preparing the idea of  Bf4  followed by  Ne5 / d2 , without allowing ... Ne4 . }
13. b5{ We continue with our plan, cementing the bishop on  c4 . }
14. Bf4{ White continues with their plan, preparing  Nd2  or  Ne5  to exert pressure on the  c4 -bishop. }
14. a5{ The logical follow-up, exerting pressure on the  b4 -pawn. White has to react energetically here, as otherwise, they are just worse. }
15. bxa5
15. b4{ A clever move. In case the knight moves, we can play ... Rxa5  and White would not have time for  Nd2 . }
16. Nd2{ This piece sacrifice is White's only way to maintain the balance. After any other move, we would just play ...  Rxa5  and Black would be better. }
16. bxc3{ We should just accept the sacrifice. }
17. Nxc4
17. dxc4
18. Qxc3{ White should continue to play for compensation. }
18. c6{ Giving back a pawn, but now we enable the move ... Qxa5 . }( { I do not recommend hanging on to our extra material with }18...Ra7 { , as after }19.Rb7 Rxb7 20.Bxb7 { , White has good compensation due to their strong bishop pair and the dangerous a-pawn. } )
19. Bxc6
19. Qxa5
20. Qxa5
20. Rxa5
21. Rb7{ The pin on the  d7 -knight is unpleasant, but fortunately, we have a way to deal with it. }
21. g5{ Forcing White's bishop to make a decision. Regardless of where it moves, we will have defensive resources. }
22. Be5
22. Rc8{ Giving back a full piece, but our c-pawn will give us enough counterplay. }
23. Rxd7{ If White wants to slow down our c-pawn, they can also play  Rxd7 . }
23. Nxd7
24. Bxd7
24. Rf8( { After both the text and }24...Rca8 { , Black has nothing to worry about, and if anything, is slightly better. } )
