13. Ne5{ The only critical move for White, exerting pressure on the  d5 -pawn and making it difficult for us to develop our  b8 -knight. }
13. Bb7{ Our best move, further defending the  d5 -pawn, and enabling the moves ... Na6  and ... Nbd7 , as now White will not have  Nc6 . }
14. Bf4{ The critical continuation and also still following Shankland's recommendation. White places the bishop on a more active square and also increases the pressure on the  d5 -pawn. }
14. Bf8{ Sam does not cover this move, but I believe it is best. By moving the bishop out of the way, we activate the rook on  e8 , which will prove to be useful in a lot of variations. If White gives us the time, we will often want to play ... h6  to threaten ... g5 , but also to make sure that White does not have the move  Bg5 .    As we will see, we will often also have the option to 'win' a piece with ... g5 , but I do not recommend this, as White will always get strong compensation after  Nxf7   Kxf7   Bxg5 . }
15. Ra2{ A typical idea in these positions. White prepares the move  Rd2  to increase the pressure on the  d5 -pawn. This move has not been played before, but I believe it is White's critical attempt for an advantage. }
15. Nbd7{ Continuing our development and trying to trade off White's active knight on  e5 . }( { Black also has the option to 'win' a piece here with }15...g5 { , but I do not recommend this, as after }16.Nxf7 Kxf7 17.Bxg5⩲ { , White has strong compensation for the piece, }{ as they have two pawns, our king is exposed, and the  d5 -pawn is also weak. } )
16. Nxd7{ It would be in our favor if White tries to simplify the position. }
16. Qxd7
17. Bg5
17. d4
18. Bxb7
18. Qxb7
19. Bxf6
19. gxf6{ Black's pawn structure may be somewhat damaged, but Black is better due to our pressure on the  b3  and  e2 -pawns. Furthermore, we can attempt to soften up White's kingside with ... h5 - h4 . }
