8. Be7{ White can play  Rd1 ,  Nc3 ,  Bf4  here in any order, but our response will always be ... O-O , ... Qb6 , and ... Rd8 . }
9. Rd1{ White should move the  f1 -rook to  d1 , as this keeps the option open to go  Rab1  and  b4  if Black plays ... d6  too early. }
9. O-O{ We just continue with our development as well. }
10. Nc3{ White's most natural continuation, keeping their options open as to how they want to position the other pieces. }
10. Qb6{ Activating the queen and clearing up the  d8 -square for our rook, as our d-pawn will require constant attention. }
11. Bf4{ White's most popular move by far and understandably so. The bishop is well placed on  f4 , as it will always exert pressure on our d-pawn once we move it to  d6 . }
11. Rd8{ We play this move first and delay ... d6 , as that could be met with a quick  Rab1  and  b4  from White, as our bishop would no longer cover the  b4 -square. }
12. Rab1{ White tries to discourage us from playing ... d6 , as that would allow  b4  again. }
12. h6{ Again, we should not allow White to play  b4 , as that will give them a nagging initiative on the queenside. ... h6  is actually quite a useful move in these positions, as it will limit the mobility of White's bishop on  f4  and knight on  f3  somewhat. We make some luft for the king, and we might have the move ... g5  in some positions too. }
13. Qb5{ This was played by Kramnik in a game to defeat Magnus Carlsen. }
13. d6{ Now is a good time to play this move. Since White's queen is somewhat in the way, we do not have to be too worried about  b4  anymore. }
14. b4
14. cxb4
15. Qxb4( { In case of }15.Rxb4 Nbd7 { , Black is already slightly for choice due to our better pawn structure. }{ Next, we can play ... Bc6  to push White's queen away. } )
15. Qxb4
16. Rxb4
16. Bc6{ Black is doing fine in this endgame, as we have a slightly better pawn structure. Next, we can either play ... Na6  or ... g5 , and after White's dark-squared bishop has moved, we can play ... Nbd7 . }
