1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3( { White's main move to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense. Here, }3...Bb4+ { has somewhat lost its punch, as White has the more suitable responses }4.Bd2 { and }4.Nbd2 { . } )
3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. g3{ The critical test of the Queen's Indian. White aims to fianchetto the light-squared bishop as well and delays  Nc3 , as we can often meet that with ... Bb4 , after which we have the positional threat of ... Bxc3 . }
4. Ba6( { Against almost any other 4th move, we play }4...Bb7 { , }{ but here this is our right continuation, as we develop the bishop with tempo and force White to defend the  c4 -pawn with a slightly awkward move. } )
5. Qa4{ This leads to a slower game and is generally chosen by players who want to avoid heavy theoretical battles. }
5. Bb7{ Now that we have lured out White's queen from  d1  to  a4 , we are going to prepare ... c5 , as White will not be able to meet that with  d5 . }
6. Bg2{ By far White's main move, continuing development. }
6. c5{ We should challenge White's center as quickly as possible. }
7. dxc5{ White's best way to deal with the pressure on the center. }
7. bxc5{ Taking with the bishop is possible as well, as we get to develop a little bit faster, but I prefer recapturing with the pawn, as we get slightly more control in the center. }
8. O-O
8. Be7{ White can play  Rd1 ,  Nc3 ,  Bf4  here in any order, but our response will always be ... O-O , ... Qb6 , and ... Rd8 . }
9. Rd1{ White should move the  f1 -rook to  d1 , as this keeps the option open to go  Rab1  and  b4  if Black plays ... d6  too early. }
9. O-O{ We just continue with our development as well. }
10. Nc3{ White's most natural continuation, keeping their options open as to how they want to position the other pieces. }
10. Qb6{ Activating the queen and clearing up the  d8 -square for our rook, as our d-pawn will require constant attention. }
11. Bf4{ White's most popular move by far and understandably so. The bishop is well placed on  f4 , as it will always exert pressure on our d-pawn once we move it to  d6 . }
11. Rd8{ We play this move first and delay ... d6 , as that could be met with a quick  Rab1  and  b4  from White, as our bishop would no longer cover the  b4 -square. }
12. Rd2{ White prepares to double the rooks on the d-file, so they can exert pressure on our d-pawn. }
12. d6( { Since we have given the d-pawn some more support with }11...Rd8 { , it is now a good time to play this move. } )
13. Rad1{ White continues with their plan and puts more pressure on our  d6 -pawn. }
13. h6{ A useful move, as now White no longer has the  Ng5 - e4  maneuver, and in some variations, we have the move ... g5  to kick White's bishop away and relieve the pressure on the  d6 -pawn. }
14. Qb5{ With this move, White is threatening to trade on  b6  and take the  d6 -pawn. }
14. Ne8{ The only move that keeps Black's position together. Our position may look a bit passive for the moment, but White does not have an easy way to increase the pressure. Generally, we will aim to continue our development here with ... Nc6 , or push White's dark-squared bishop back with ... g5  to relieve the pressure on our  d6 -pawn. }
15. e4{ White's most popular move. The idea is quite straightforward: White wants to play  e5  quickly, to open up the position and take advantage of their lead in development. }
15. g5{ Pushing White's dark-squared bishop back to relieve the pressure on our  d6 -pawn. If you are looking for a double-edged game, this is the move I recommend. }
16. Be3
16. Nd7{ Developing the knight and stopping White from breaking in the center with  e5 . }
17. h4{ With this move, White is aiming to soften our kingside pawn structure, but we will keep our structure nicely intact. }
17. g4{ Pushing White's knight from  f3  back. }
18. Ne1{ Black also has absolutely nothing to worry about in the event of  Ne1 . We have lots of fine options, but our most accurate is the text move. }
18. Qxb5
19. Nxb5
19. Ne5
20. b3
20. a6{ Pushing White's knight back and thus relieving the pressure on the  d6 -pawn. }
21. Nc3
21. Bf6{ Activating the bishop and eyeing the knight on  c3 , which will give us some tactical possibilities. }
22. Bxh6
22. Nf3+
23. Bxf3
23. Bxc3
24. Bxg4
24. Bxd2{ Followed by ... Bxe4 , and White will have to work hard for the draw. }
