3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. g3
4. Ba6
5. Qb3( { A bit of a sideline. White defends the pawn on  c4  while still eyeing the  d5 -square with the queen, so }5...c5 { could be met with }6.d5 { . However, the queen }{ on  b3  is a bit vulnerable to threats from the black pieces, and we will take advantage of that with the text move. } )
5. Nc6{ Threatening ... Na5 , forking the queen and the pawn on  c4 . }
6. Bd2{ White takes away the  a5 -square from the black knight, but here there is another way to pester White before development can be completed. }
6. Bb7{ Threatening ... Nxd4 . }
7. d5( { Of course not }7.Bg2? { , as this runs into }7...Nxd4–+ { and Black wins a pawn. } )
7. Ne7{ Attacking the pawn on  d5  four times, while it is only defended once. White is forced to trade on  e6 . }
8. dxe6
8. fxe6
9. Bg2
9. Nf5
10. O-O
10. Bc5{ Black equalized easily. We have no weaknesses, active piece play, and after we play ... O-O  in the near future, we can try to use the half-open f-file to develop an initiative. }
11. Qd3{ One last detail that we have to keep in mind is how to meet this move. }
11. Be4{ This is important, as it disrupts White's queen from the  d3 -square. Otherwise, White would be able to get  12.Nc3  and  e4  in and our pieces would be pushed back. }
