3. Nf3( { White's main move to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense. Here, }3...Bb4+ { has somewhat lost its punch, as White has the more suitable responses }4.Bd2 { and }4.Nbd2 { . } )
3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. g3
4. Ba6
5. Qb3( { A bit of a sideline. White defends the pawn on  c4  while still eyeing the  d5 -square with the queen, so }5...c5 { could be met with }6.d5 { . However, the queen }{ on  b3  is a bit vulnerable to threats from the black pieces, and we will take advantage of that with the text move. } )
5. Nc6{ Threatening ... Na5 , forking the queen and the pawn on  c4 . }
6. Nbd2{ Defending the pawn on  c4 , so ... Na5  will not be a fork anymore. }
6. Na5{ This move no longer creates a fork, but we should play it anyway, as it will allow us to challenge White's center with a quick ... c5 . }
7. Qa4{ Creating the threat of  b4 , which would win a piece. Furthermore, White also has the positional threat of  e4 , grabbing the full center. }
7. Bb7{ Stopping  e4  and making sure that  b4  no longer wins a piece. }( { It would not be good to challenge White's center right away with }7...c5?! { , as after }8.e4 { , we are unable to play }8...cxd4? { due to }9.b4+– { and White wins a piece. } )
8. Bg2{ White continues development. }
8. c5{ Now is the right time to challenge White's center. By not having played ... c6 , the difference is that now we can meet White's move with ... c5 . }
9. dxc5
9. bxc5{ We generally want to recapture with the b-pawn on  c5 , as our pawn on  c5  controls some important squares, and in case we recapture with the bishop, we will have to be careful that we do not get forked with a potential  b4 . }
10. O-O
10. Be7{ Now we are ready to castle on the next move. }
11. Re1{ With this move, White is aiming to play  e4 - e5  quickly, to force our knight on  f6  to go to an awkward square. }
11. Qc7{ We are anticipating White's  e4 - e5  push. Furthermore, we will see later why we are delaying kingside castling. }( 11...O-O { is Black's most popular move, but after }12.e4 { , }{ White gets a slight initiative with  e5  coming next. } )
12. e4
12. Nc6{ Further preparing for White's  e5  push, as we will be able to exert a lot of pressure on White's  e5 -pawn. Furthermore, if White does not play  e5 , we could even consider playing ... e5  ourselves and later plant our knight on  d4 . }
13. e5
13. Ng4
14. h3
14. Nh6{ The knight may look offside on  h6 , but we want to bring it back into the game on the next move with ... Nf5 . }
15. g4{ White can also stop our knight from moving to  f5 , but here we will break with ... f5 . }
15. f5( 15...f6 { leads to the same thing, as White's best move is still }16.exf6 { . } )
16. exf6
16. gxf6
17. Ne4
17. Nf7{ With a double-edged game, as we are ready to break open the kingside with moves like ... h5  or ... Rg8  followed by ... f5  or ... h5 . }
