2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3( { White's main move to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense. Here, }3...Bb4+ { has somewhat lost its punch, as White has the more suitable responses }4.Bd2 { and }4.Nbd2 { . } )
3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. a3
4. Bb7
5. Nc3
5. d5{ Since White has stopped us from playing ... Bb4 , we should fight for control in the center this way. }
6. Bg5{ White's second most popular move, delaying the trade on  d5  and pinning the knight on  f6 . }
6. Be7{ Continuing our development and neutralizing the pin on the  f6 -knight. }
7. Bxf6
7. Bxf6
8. cxd5
8. exd5
9. Qa4+{ A tricky check that forces us to place one of our pieces on a suboptimal square. }
9. Nd7{ Our best way to block the check, continuing our development. }
10. g3
10. a6{ Enabling ... b5  to push White's queen away and gain space on the queenside. }( { After }10...O-O?! { , White has the unpleasant }11.Bh3!⩲ { and there is no comfortable way to deal with the threat on the knight. } )
11. Bh3
11. b5
12. Qc2
12. c5{ We should strike in the center before White is able to consolidate. }
13. dxc5
13. Nxc5{ Black has a fine game, as our activity and bishop pair compensate for the isolated pawn. An important line is: }
14. Nxb5
14. Qa5+
15. Nc3
15. d4
16. b4
16. Qc7{ The best square for our queen. }
17. Nd5
17. Bxd5
18. Qxc5
18. Qxc5
19. bxc5
19. d3
20. O-O-O
20. Be4{ Black also gets good compensation here too due to our strong bishop pair and White's exposed king. }
