2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3( { White's main move to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense. Here, }3...Bb4+ { has somewhat lost its punch, as White has the more suitable responses }4.Bd2 { and }4.Nbd2 { . } )
3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. a3
4. Bb7
5. Nc3
5. d5{ Since White has stopped us from playing ... Bb4 , we should fight for control in the center this way. }
6. cxd5
6. Nxd5( { We generally want to recapture with the knight on  d5 , as it keeps our bishop on  b7  open, and White has the slightly better pawn structure after }6...exd5 { . } )
7. Bd2{ In case of ... Nxc3 , White is now able to recapture with the bishop. }
7. Nd7{ We should just continue developing our pieces. }
8. Qc2{ With this move, White is aiming to play  e4  quickly. }
8. c5{ We should exert pressure on White's center as quickly as possible. }
9. Nxd5{ There is also a tricky line starting with this move. }
9. exd5
10. dxc5{ If White does not go for this line, Black is already slightly for choice due to our active pieces. }
10. bxc5
11. e4{ An interesting pawn sacrifice and definitely a line that we should be aware of. }
11. dxe4{ Of course, we should accept the sacrifice. }
12. Ng5{ The point behind White's play is that now they have quite a few threats, such as  Nxf7  followed by  Qb3 +, or  Qb3  right away. }
12. Qb6{ The only move to maintain the balance, addressing White's threats with  Qb3 . }
13. Bc4{ The direct approach. }
13. Ne5{ The only way to properly defend the  f7 -pawn. If we get the time here to consolidate with ... Be7  and ... O-O , Black is just better, but White still has the pesky  Bf4 . }
14. Bf4
14. Nd3+{ The best way to address White's threats. }
15. Bxd3
15. exd3
16. Qxd3
16. Rd8{ Attacking the white queen and also making sure that White no longer has the option to castle queenside. }
17. Qe3+
17. Be7
18. O-O{ This position still looks a bit scary, as we cannot castle for the moment since that would hang our bishop on  e7 . Fortunately, we have a clever way to organize our pieces. }
18. Qc6{ Threatening checkmate on  g2  and thus slowing down White's aggressive intentions. }
19. Nf3
19. Rd7{ Defending the bishop on  e7 . We are finally ready to castle on the next move, and Black is already slightly for choice due to our bishop pair. }
