9. Nd7{ Our best move, developing the knight and making sure that White does not have any annoying checks on the  a4 - e8  diagonal. Furthermore, this move enables us to play ... Rc8  quickly, which can be quite useful in a lot of lines. }
10. Bf4{ Developing the bishop and stopping us from playing ... Qc7 . }
10. cxd4{ We should open up the c-file quickly, so we can immediately challenge White's queen on  c2 , and White does not have the option to play  d5 . }
11. cxd4
11. Rc8{ Developing the rook with tempo, as we attack White's queen, which does not have a very comfortable square to go to. }
12. Qb3{ White's best square for the queen. With this move, White sacrifices the pawn on  e4 , but taking it is quite risky for Black. }
12. Be7{ The more solid approach. }( 12...Bxe4 { is too risky, as after }13.Ba6↑ { , }{ our rook on  c8  is lacking good squares to go to, and White has a big lead in development. } )
13. Bd3
13. Nf6{ It is important to play this move before White has castled, so they cannot defend the  e4 -pawn with  Rfe1 . }
14. Qb5+{ White's best move, forcing us to slightly misplace our light-squared bishop. }
14. Bc6
15. Qb1
15. O-O
16. O-O
16. b5{ Black has a fine game here due to our space advantage on the queenside. }( { An important point is that }17.e5?! { backfires due to }17...Nh5 18.Bxh7+? Kh8 { , }{ as the bishop on  f4  is under attack, while we threaten to trap the bishop on  h7  with ... g6 . }{ After }19.Bg3 g6 ( { Black is also winning after }19...Bxf3 20.gxf3 g6 21.Bxg6 fxg6 22.Qxg6 Ng7–+ { . } )20.Bxg6 fxg6 21.Qxg6 Ng7–+ { , White simply does not have sufficient compensation for the bishop, and Black is just winning. } )
