11. f5{ Defending our knight on  e4  and expanding on the kingside at the same time. Black has a good game here if we are able to consolidate, so White should act quickly. }
12. d5{ White sacrifices a pawn to break open the position and make their lead in development felt. }
12. Nd7( { Instead of accepting White's pawn sacrifice, we sacrifice a pawn ourselves. }12...Na6 { is fine as well. It will likely lead to the same thing, as our knight is headed }{ to  c5  in the foreseeable future. } )
13. Bxe4{ With this move, White accepts our pawn sacrifice. }
13. fxe4
14. Qxe4{ White is threatening  Qxe6 + and  Qg6 +, but fortunately, we can effectively deal with these threats. }
14. Qf6{ Defending our  e6 -pawn and also addressing White's threat of  Qg6 +. With this move, we sacrifice another pawn, but we get excellent compensation if White were to take it. }
15. O-O{ White delays taking on  e6  and completes development. }
15. Nc5{ Attacking White's queen on  e4  and making sure that White can no longer take our  e6 -pawn. }
16. Qd4{ Escaping the threat of our knight and offering the queen trade. }
16. Rf8{ We do not mind a queen trade, but we should certainly not trade on  d4 , as that will allow White to rectify their pawn structure. }( 16...e5? { would be a big mistake due to }17.Nxe5! dxe5? 18.Bxe5 { and White wins. } )
17. e4{ White maintains the tension and strengthens their center. }
17. e5{ Now that our rook is no longer on  h8 , we can play this move to push White's queen back and also limit the scope of White's bishop on  g3 . }
18. Qe3{ The best square for White's queen, as it protects the  e4 -pawn. }
18. O-O-O{ Despite being down a pawn, Black is already slightly for choice. We have the better pawn structure and White's bishop on  g3  is quite passive. We can continue by playing ... Kb8  and expanding on the kingside with a timely ... h5 . }
