1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Nf3( { White's main move to avoid the Nimzo-Indian Defense. Here, }3...Bb4+ { has somewhat lost its punch, as White has the more suitable responses }4.Bd2 { and }4.Nbd2 { . } )
3. b6{ One of the main ideas of the Nimzo-Indian Defense is to prevent White from playing the move  e2 - e4 . With the bishop coming to  b7  in many variations, we will hold on to that goal. It is because of this that the Queen's Indian is regarded as the sister opening of the Nimzo. }( { In recent years, the Queen's Indian has gone out of fashion, to some extent, at the top level, with many players switching to the Queen's Gambit Declined with }3...d5 { . However, in recent months, it has made a comeback with the two best players in the world, Magnus Carlsen and Ding Liren, playing it.    Just like the Nimzo, the beauty of this opening is its flexibility, as we have not yet committed any of our pawns in the center and, therefore, keep our options open. } )
4. Nc3{ This natural-looking move is actually a rare guest at the grandmaster level. The reason for this is that now we will always have the option to play ... Bb4  quickly, with the idea to give White doubled c-pawns. }
4. Bb7( { We just continue our development with this natural move. I do not recommend }4...Bb4 { , as that will deviate from our Nimzo-Indian repertoire. In  Part 1 , I suggest   }4...O-O { against  4.Nf3 . } )
5. Bg5{ This used to be one of White's main lines against the Queen's Indian, but these days this is not a line we should be worried about whatsoever. White develops the dark-squared bishop to its most active square, but this developing move can also backfire. }
5. h6{ I suggest we start by forcing White to make a decision with the dark-squared bishop. }
6. Bh4{ White's logical response, keeping the pin on our knight and not conceding the bishop pair. }
6. Bb4( { We develop our dark-squared bishop and pin the knight on  c3 . }6...Be7 { followed by a }{ quick ... c5  is also fine for Black, but I prefer the text, as it is more active. } )
7. e3{ White just continues development. }
7. g5{ Breaking the pin so our knight can jump forward on the next move. }
8. Bg3{ White's only move. }
8. Ne4{ The point behind our last move, increasing the pressure on  c3 . }
9. Qc2{ White's best way to further defend the knight on  c3 . }
9. d6{ We neutralize White's bishop on  g3  somewhat, and we open up the  d7 -square for our knight. }( { Starting with }9...Bxc3+ { will likely lead to the same thing, as after }10.bxc3 d6 { , White's best move is still }11.Bd3 { . } )
10. Bd3{ Developing the light-squared bishop and attacking our knight on  e4 . }
10. Bxc3+{ We should take the opportunity to ruin White's pawn structure before it is too late. }
11. bxc3
11. f5{ Defending our knight on  e4  and expanding on the kingside at the same time. Black has a good game here if we are able to consolidate, so White should act quickly. }
12. d5{ White sacrifices a pawn to break open the position and make their lead in development felt. }
12. Nd7( { Instead of accepting White's pawn sacrifice, we sacrifice a pawn ourselves. }12...Na6 { is fine as well. It will likely lead to the same thing, as our knight is headed }{ to  c5  in the foreseeable future. } )
13. Nd4{ Instead of accepting our pawn sacrifice, White creates the big threat of  Nxe6 . }
13. Ndc5{ The only proper way to address White's threat. }
14. O-O{ White completes development and maintains the tension in the center. }
14. Qe7{ The most accurate. We maintain the tension in the center as well and slightly improve our queen. }
15. f3{ Attacking our knight on  e4 . White has to play this move, as otherwise, we would get a significant advantage. }
15. Nxd3{ The only way to conveniently deal with White's threat, as we clear the  c5 -square for our  e4 -knight. }
16. fxe4( { This is the right knight to capture. }16.Qxd3?! { would be inaccurate, as after }16...Nc5 { , Black is clearly for choice }{ since ... Rf8  and ... O-O-O  are coming next. } )
16. Nc5{ Our only move, defending against White's threats of  Qxd3  and  Nxe6 . }
17. e5( { White's only move to maintain the balance, creating more tension in the center. Black is clearly better after }17.exf5 exd5 18.cxd5 Bxd5⩱ { . } )
17. O-O{ Our only move to maintain the balance. We often go for queenside castling in this variation, but in this case, our king will be safer on the kingside. }
18. exd6{ White's only move to maintain the balance, as we will end up with a weak pawn on  d6 , which will compensate somewhat for White's weaknesses. If White does not play this move, we can take on  e5  ourselves, which will give us a good game. }
18. cxd6
19. Rad1{ Bringing the rook into the game and eyeing our  d6 -pawn. }
19. Rad8( { We bring our a-rook into the game as well to add some support to the  d6 -pawn. }19...Rf6 { is fine as well and will likely lead to the same thing. } )
20. dxe6{ White takes our pawn and is now also threatening to take on  f5 . Fortunately, we can easily deal with this. }
20. Be4{ Attacking White's queen and making sure that White cannot take on  f5 . }
21. Qe2{ The best square for White's queen. }
21. Rf6{ The most accurate, as the rook will further protect the  d6 -pawn in the future. Next, we are going to play ... Nxe6  and Black has absolutely nothing to worry about here. }( { We should not play }21...Nxe6?! { due to }22.Nb5⩲ { and White wins a pawn, as we are simply unable to defend }{ our  d6 -pawn. } )
