1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. g3{ With this move, White intends to play the Catalan and at the same time avoids the Queen's Indian. However, it does allow another option. }
3. c5{ The point of this repertoire is to avoid the annoying Catalan and to get fighting positions. This move offers just what we are looking for. Black is not only fine in the Fianchetto Benoni, but it also offers Black plenty of fighting chances in the arising positions. }
4. d5{ The critical response to  3...c5 . White grabs more space and enters the Fianchetto Benoni. }
4. d6{ We will have to play this move at some point, as it allows us to continue our development, but we also stop White from potentially playing  d6  themselves. }( { Starting with }4...exd5 5.cxd5 d6 { is fine as well and will likely lead to the same thing. } )
5. Nc3{ White continues development and also stops us from potentially playing ... b5  with this move. }
5. exd5{ We should not delay this trade too long, as otherwise, it will give White some extra options. }
6. cxd5{ We are now in the Benoni structure. The Fianchetto Benoni is one of the better lines for Black in the Benoni. The reason for this is that we have a better chance of achieving the ... b5  push, as White's bishop on  g2  will not help White stop that push. }
6. g6{ We prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop, as it will be most active there. }
7. Bg2( { White can also start with }7.Nf3 { , but it does not change much, as after }7...Bg7 { , White's best move is still }8.Bg2 { . } )
7. Bg7
8. Nf3
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Re8{ We have reached the tabiya of the  g3  Benoni. White has quite a few options here, but Black will get a good game against all of them, and we will also get our chances to fight for the win.    In most cases, our plan will be to continue our development with ... Nbd7  and prepare the ... b5  push with ... a6 . If White stops it with  a4 , we will reinforce the ... b5  push with ... Rb8 . }
10. a4{ Since White firmly stops ... b5  for the moment, we should go for another plan. }
10. Ne4
11. Nxe4
11. Rxe4
12. Nd2{ White's idea behind  10.a4 . White wants to play  Nc4  followed by  Bf4  if we retreat our rook. However, we have other intentions. }
12. Rb4{ Stopping White from playing  Nc4  and taking advantage of the fact that White has weakened the  b4 -square with  10.a4 . At first, this might look a bit scary, as our rook might appear to be a bit stuck on  b4 , but it will take White quite some time to attack it, and in the meantime, we can organize counterplay. }
13. Ra2{ White unpins the b-pawn so they can play  b3  and  Ba3  quickly. }
13. a5{ We want to play ... b5  to free the rook on  b4  somewhat. }
14. b3
14. b5
15. Ba3{ White can win the exchange, but Black will get excellent compensation. }
15. bxa4
16. Bxb4
16. axb4
17. Rxa4
17. Rxa4
18. bxa4
18. Ba6{ Black has excellent compensation for the sacrificed exchange due to our strong bishop pair, and our strong passed pawns on the queenside. Next, we can continue bringing our pieces into the game with ... Nd7  and ... Qa5 , and we can certainly get chances if White is not careful. }
