2. c4
2. e6
3. g3{ With this move, White intends to play the Catalan and at the same time avoids the Queen's Indian. However, it does allow another option. }
3. c5{ The point of this repertoire is to avoid the annoying Catalan and to get fighting positions. This move offers just what we are looking for. Black is not only fine in the Fianchetto Benoni, but it also offers Black plenty of fighting chances in the arising positions. }
4. d5{ The critical response to  3...c5 . White grabs more space and enters the Fianchetto Benoni. }
4. d6{ We will have to play this move at some point, as it allows us to continue our development, but we also stop White from potentially playing  d6  themselves. }( { Starting with }4...exd5 5.cxd5 d6 { is fine as well and will likely lead to the same thing. } )
5. Nc3{ White continues development and also stops us from potentially playing ... b5  with this move. }
5. exd5{ We should not delay this trade too long, as otherwise, it will give White some extra options. }
6. cxd5{ We are now in the Benoni structure. The Fianchetto Benoni is one of the better lines for Black in the Benoni. The reason for this is that we have a better chance of achieving the ... b5  push, as White's bishop on  g2  will not help White stop that push. }
6. g6{ We prepare to fianchetto our dark-squared bishop, as it will be most active there. }
7. Bg2( { White can also start with }7.Nf3 { , but it does not change much, as after }7...Bg7 { , White's best move is still }8.Bg2 { . } )
7. Bg7
8. Nf3
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Re8{ We have reached the tabiya of the  g3  Benoni. White has quite a few options here, but Black will get a good game against all of them, and we will also get our chances to fight for the win.    In most cases, our plan will be to continue our development with ... Nbd7  and prepare the ... b5  push with ... a6 . If White stops it with  a4 , we will reinforce the ... b5  push with ... Rb8 . }
10. Re1{ This move has become quite popular in recent years. White improves the position a bit as  e2 - e4  is now possible in the near future. Furthermore,  10.Re1  is a bit of a waiting move, as White is waiting to see how Black will proceed and then react accordingly. }
10. a6{ With this move we prepare ... b5 . }
11. a4{ White stops ... b5 . }
11. Nbd7{ As so often in the Fianchetto Benoni, this is our best way forward, developing the knight and clearing the  b8 -square for our rook. }
12. Bf4{ White's critical continuation. White immediately exerts pressure on the  d6 -pawn, which is somewhat awkward to defend. Instead of defending it passively, we have other intentions. }
12. Ng4{ Dealing with White's threat to our  d6 -pawn in a tactical way. }
13. a5{ With this move, White makes sure that we can no longer meet  Bxd6  with ... Qb6 . Hence,  Bxd6  is now a real threat that we should defend against. }
13. Nde5{ The best way to address White's threat to our  d6 -pawn. }
14. Ne4{ White activates the knight and increases the pressure on our  d6 -pawn. White has only played like this once at the grandmaster level but on numerous occasions in correspondence chess. Therefore, we should take this move seriously. }
14. b5( { Technically a novelty, although some games have continued here with }14...b6 { , which leads to the same thing after }15.axb6 { . } )( 14...h6 { is Black's most popular choice in this position, but after }15.h3 Nxf3+ 16.exf3 Ne5 17.Bf1⩲ { , White is slightly better and has excellent results in correspondence chess (2.5/3), }{ as  Bd2  is coming next, followed by a potential  f4 . } )
15. axb6{ White has to go for this trade, as otherwise, Black is already for choice. }
15. Qxb6{ Now, our queen is active, as it is eyeing the pawn on  b2  but also the pawn on  f2  potentially. }
16. h3
16. Nxf3+{ We should trade knights so we clear up the  e5 -square for our knight on  g4 . }
17. exf3{ Even though this doubles White's pawns, this is White's best recapture, as it opens up the e-file for their rook and now ... Ne5  won't create any threats. }
17. Ne5{ If Black will get one more move here, we will just play ... Bf5  and we will be fine. However, White has a way to disturb the harmony in our position somewhat. }
18. b4{ White's only try for an advantage. }
18. cxb4{ After some consideration, I decided on this as my recommendation. The variations are more forcing than those arising from  18...c4 . }( 18...c4 { is also possible, but after }19.Bg5 f5 20.Nf6+ Bxf6 21.Bxf6 Bd7 22.Qd2↑ { , White keeps some initiative, as our king is somewhat exposed. } )
19. Be3
19. Qb8{ The best square for our queen, as we keep defending the  d6 -pawn. }
20. f4
20. Nd7
21. Bd4{ White's best move, trading off the dark-squared bishops to weaken our king somewhat. }
21. Bxd4{ We should trade the bishops right away. }
22. Qxd4{ White can potentially build up a strong attack here if they will get the time to play  h4 - h5 - h6 . Therefore, we should create counterplay as quickly as possible. }
22. b3{ We have to set our pawns in motion right away. }
23. h4{ White can also just continue with their plan. }
23. a5{ The only move to hold the balance. The point behind this move is to be able to play ... Qb4  in the foreseeable future to take the sting out of White's attack. }
24. h5
24. b2{ Once again, the only move to maintain the balance. }
25. h6{ Creating the threat of checkmate on  g7  and sacrificing the rook on  a1 . }( { We can meet }25.Rab1 { with }25...Qb4= { and Black is fine, as White cannot escape the queen trade. } )
25. bxa1=Q( { Fortunately, we are able to take the rook on  a1 , as our new queen covers the  g7 -square! Fun fact: }25...bxa1=B { is equally good, and leads to the same thing after }26.Qxa1 { . } )
26. Qxa1{ The only move for White to maintain the balance. }
26. f6{ The only proper move to stop White's checkmate threat. }
27. Bh3{ White's only move to maintain the balance, threatening  Bxd7 , which would lead to a crushing attack. }
27. Rxe4{ Our only move, we absolutely have to get rid of the knight on  e4 . }
28. Rxe4{ White, of course, has to recapture. }
28. Ne5{ Another important only move, blocking the e-file and the  a1 - h8  diagonal. }
29. fxe5( { White has to take the knight sooner or later. Black is also fine after }29.Bxc8 Qxc8 30.fxe5 fxe5= { . } )
29. fxe5{ After some wild complications, we finally land in this endgame. White has enough compensation for the pawn, but also nothing more than that. Black is fine here. }
