12. h3{ This is often a useful move for White in these positions, as White takes away the  g4 -square from our pieces, and now a potential ... Nh5  can be met with  g4 . }
12. Rb8{ Preparing ... b5 . }
13. Nc4{ Attacking the pawn on  d6 . }
13. Ne5
14. Na3{ White retreats the knight and stops us from playing ... b5 . Furthermore, White wants to play  f4  quickly to kick our knight from  e5 . }( { Again, Black has nothing to worry about }14.Nxe5 { , as after }14...Rxe5 { , }{ we will follow up with a quick ... b5 . } )
14. Nh5{ Discouraging White from playing  f4 , as now the  g3 -pawn would start hanging immediately. }
15. g4{ White can try to push our pieces back, but we have other intentions. }
15. Qh4{ Sacrificing the knight and setting the board on fire. }
16. Ne4{ White's best move, threatening to trap our queen with  Bg5 . Furthermore, the knight is also eyeing the pawn on  d6 , so White could potentially pick that pawn up later. }( { After }16.gxh5?! Bxh3∓ { , we will get a crushing attack. } )
16. h6{ The only way to conveniently address the threat of  Bg5 . }
17. Qe1{ White's best move and a clever one. With this move, White prepares  f4 , which would offer a queen trade. }( { Black is also doing well in the complications arising from }17.f4 Nxg4⇆ { . } )
17. Nf6( { This is fine as well. If the following line appeals more to you than }17...f5 { , then feel free to go for it. } )
18. Nxd6{ White has to take the pawn on  d6 , as otherwise, we would have a tremendous initiative for free. }
18. Bxg4{ Vice versa, we have to strike back. }
19. f4( 19.Nxe8 { would lead to the same thing, as after }19...Rxe8 { , White's best move is still }20.f4 { and after }20...Qxe1 21.Rxe1 Nd3 { , we have a transposition. } )
19. Qxe1{ There is no other choice but to trade queens. }
20. Rxe1
20. Nd3{ Addressing the threat on our knight on  e5 , and making use of the pin on the e-file to attack White's rook. }
21. Nxe8
21. Rxe8{ The only move. }
22. exd3( { White's best move and the only way to maintain the balance. After }22.hxg4 Nxe1 23.g5 hxg5 24.fxg5 Ng4 25.Bh3 { , }{ White won't grab our knight on  e1  for free because of }25...Bd4+ 26.Kf1 Nf2! { and Black's position is preferable. } )
22. Rxe1+
23. Kf2
23. Re2+{ The only move not to lose material. }
24. Kf1
24. Bh5{ After some wild complications in which both sides had to make a lot of only moves, we finally land in this position, where White will still need to be accurate to maintain the balance. An effective plan here will be ... Nd7  followed by ... Bd4 , to continue the attack on the white king. }
