8. Nf3
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Re8{ We have reached the tabiya of the  g3  Benoni. White has quite a few options here, but Black will get a good game against all of them, and we will also get our chances to fight for the win.    In most cases, our plan will be to continue our development with ... Nbd7  and prepare the ... b5  push with ... a6 . If White stops it with  a4 , we will reinforce the ... b5  push with ... Rb8 . }
10. Nd2{ This used to be the main line many years ago, but Black has a very effective antidote. The lines here are fun and they truly illustrate why we play the Benoni instead of the Catalan.    That being said, I suggest you practice diligently with the move trainer, as the variations get extremely sharp from here. The idea behind  10.Nd2  is to play  Nc4  quickly followed by  Bf4  and exert a lot of pressure on the  d6 -pawn. }
10. a6{ Preparing ... b5 . }
11. a4{ White should play this move to stop our ... b5  push. }
11. Nbd7{ Now we are able to meet  Nc4  with ... Ne5 . }
12. h3{ This is often a useful move for White in these positions, as White takes away the  g4 -square from our pieces, and now a potential ... Nh5  can be met with  g4 . }
