9. Re8{ We have reached the tabiya of the  g3  Benoni. White has quite a few options here, but Black will get a good game against all of them, and we will also get our chances to fight for the win.    In most cases, our plan will be to continue our development with ... Nbd7  and prepare the ... b5  push with ... a6 . If White stops it with  a4 , we will reinforce the ... b5  push with ... Rb8 . }
10. Bf4{ This has become the new main line in the  g3  Benoni. }
10. h6{ The point behind this move is to play ... g5  quickly, forcing the bishop on  f4  to retreat so White will no longer have pressure on the  d6 -pawn. }
11. h3{ This is White's third most popular move in this position, and I actually faced it myself once in a Titled Tuesday. }
11. g5{ We should stick to our plan and push White's bishop back. }
12. Bc1{ The best-retreating square for White's dark-squared bishop, as this keeps the  d2 -square open for the knight. }
12. Bf5{ We bring our bishop into the game, and now we see why ... h6  and ... g5  were useful, as White cannot push our light-squared bishop away with  Nh4 . }
13. Nd2{ With this move, White is aiming to reroute the knight to  c4 , but also to expand in the center with  e4  or  f4 . }
13. Na6{ Black has a good game here, as we have plenty of ways to create counterplay. Without the inclusion of  h4  and ... g4 , this is the better-developing square for the knight, as it is harder to fight for the  e5 -square here. Also, we have the idea of ... Qd7  followed by ... b5 , and in case White plays  a4 , our knight can now go to the  b4 -square. }
