16. Nc4{ The only move not to get worse. With this move, White is eyeing our  d6 -pawn and makes it difficult for us to bring our  b8 -knight into the game. }
16. Qe7{ Preparing ... Nbd7 . }
17. Nb5{ Again, the only move not to get worse with White. White forces our knight on  f6  back to  e8  so we cannot start our aggressive operations right away. }
17. Ne8
18. e4{ This move will enable White to retreat the knight from  c4  to  e3 . This is also GM Srinath Narayanan's suggestion in his Catalan Lifetime Repertoire. I do agree with him that this line is the most testing in the Fianchetto Benoni. However, Black can maintain the balance with accurate play. }
18. a6{ Pushing White's knight back. }
19. Nc3
19. Nd7{ We have to play this move first to make sure that White does not have  Nb6 . }
20. a4{ White's best move, stopping ... b5  and maintaining the knight on  c4 . }
20. Nef6{ Now that White's knights have been pushed back, it is time to bring the knight back into play. Our knight is headed to  h5  to exert pressure on the  g3 -pawn. }
21. Qf4{ The direct approach, exerting pressure on our  d6 -pawn. }
21. Nh5{ We will still continue with this move, even if it means giving up the  g4 -pawn. }
22. Qxg4{ White has to take the pawn, as otherwise, the last move was just pointless. }
22. Ne5{ We want to trade off the knights so our bishop gets access to the  e5 -square. }
23. Nxe5
23. Bxe5{ Black has good compensation here due to our excellent piece coordination. White needs to act quickly, as we could otherwise develop a dangerous initiative starting with ... Kh8  and ... Rg8 . }
24. Rf5
