6. e5{ Now, White is forced to retreat. }
7. Nb5{ This move has also been played by some grandmasters, but it is not one that we should be worried about at all. }
7. d4{ Just like against any other knight move from White, we address White's threat on our  d5 -pawn by pushing it up. }
8. f4{ White should absolutely undermine our center as quickly as possible, as otherwise, they will be significantly worse. }( { Some players have also continued here with }8.O-O?! { but after }8...a6∓ { , }{ Black is already significantly better, as the knight has to retreat to the poor  a3 -square. } )
8. a6{ Instead of responding to White's pressure on our center, we create a counter-threat on White's  b5 -knight. }
9. fxe5{ This move is also forced, as otherwise, the white knight would retreat to a poor square. }
9. axb5
10. exf6
10. bxc4{ This is the right pawn to grab since we do not mind a trade on  g7  at all, as it will comfortably develop our dark-squared bishop. }
11. O-O
11. Nd7{ The most accurate. Black is certainly not on the worse side of the complications. With this move, we aim to take the  f6 -pawn with our knight. }( { Furthermore, }12.fxg7 { can be met with }12...Bxg7 { , after which Black is already significantly better, and   }12.Qxd4?? { runs into }12...Bc5 { , which wins the white queen. } )
