1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. g3{ With this move, White intends to play the Catalan and at the same time avoids the Queen's Indian. However, it does allow another option. }
3. c5{ The point of this repertoire is to avoid the annoying Catalan and to get fighting positions. This move offers just what we are looking for. Black is not only fine in the  g3  Benoni, but it also offers Black plenty of fighting chances in the arising positions. }
4. Nf3( { White's only reasonable option if they want to avoid the  g3  Benoni. With this move, White is keeping the position somewhat safe and is avoiding the double-edged positions we saw after }4.d5 { . However, this move does have quite some venom to it and we should therefore play accurately. } )
4. cxd4
5. Nxd4
5. d5{ The game becomes somewhat of a reversed Grünfeld now. It is important that we delay playing ... Nc6 , as then White can always trade their knight on  d4  for our knight. }
6. Bg2
6. e5{ Now, White is forced to retreat. }
7. Nf3{ With this move, White attacks both  d5  and  e5 . Fortunately for us, we can solve both problems by tactical means. }
7. d4
8. O-O( 8.Nxe5?? { would be a huge blunder due to }8...Qa5+–+ { and we win the knight on  e5 . } )
8. Nc6{ Now that White has castled, they are threatening to take the pawn on  e5 , and so we should play this logical developing move to defend it. }
9. a3{ Preparing the  b4  push to gain space on the queenside and to be able to go  b5  and kick our knight away. }
9. a5{ There are other options as well, but this is the easiest. White has nothing better than to transpose to the main line. }
10. e3
10. Be7
11. exd4
11. exd4{ We do not want to let White play  b2 - b4 , as then we would always have to worry about a potential  b5 , and also White can play  Bb2  to exert more pressure on the  d4 -pawn. }
12. Re1
12. O-O
13. Bf4
13. h6{ This move will always be useful. First of all, we make an escape square for the king so we can never get checkmated on the back rank. But more importantly: we deprive White's dark-squared bishop somewhat of its mobility and in some lines we will want to go ... g5  after White has played  Nbd2 , as the bishop does not have many squares to go to. }
