4. Nf3( { White's only reasonable option if they want to avoid the  g3  Benoni. With this move, White is keeping the position somewhat safe and is avoiding the double-edged positions we saw after }4.d5 { . However, this move does have quite some venom to it and we should therefore play accurately. } )
4. cxd4
5. Nxd4
5. d5{ The game becomes somewhat of a reversed Grünfeld now. It is important that we delay playing ... Nc6 , as then White can always trade their knight on  d4  for our knight. }
6. Bg2
6. e5{ Now, White is forced to retreat. }
7. Nf3{ With this move, White attacks both  d5  and  e5 . Fortunately for us, we can solve both problems by tactical means. }
7. d4
8. O-O( 8.Nxe5?? { would be a huge blunder due to }8...Qa5+–+ { and we win the knight on  e5 . } )
8. Nc6{ Now that White has castled, they are threatening to take the pawn on  e5 , and so we should play this logical developing move to defend it. }
9. e3
9. Be7
10. exd4
10. exd4
11. Bf4{ This is White's best attempt for an advantage. White prepares  Ne5 , in order to activate the bishop on  g2  on the long diagonal. Furthermore, if we were to trade knights on  e5 , the pawn on  d4  could become weak. }
11. O-O
12. Ne5
12. Qb6{ Defending  c6  once more and attacking the pawn on  b2  at the same time. }
13. Nd2{ Developing the knight and ignoring the threat on the  b2 -pawn. }
13. Nxe5{ Taking the pawn on  b2  would be unwise, as White would get too much activity, but the following sequence gives Black an excellent game. }
14. Bxe5
14. Ng4{ We will often see this theme after White has developed the knight to  d2 . White is forced to give up the dark-squared bishop for the knight, as otherwise, it would get trapped. }
15. Nf3( 15.Bf4 g5!∓  )
15. Nxe5
16. Nxe5
16. Bf5{ Black has absolutely nothing to worry about, as we have the bishop pair. }
