[White "18) 2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 c5"]
[Black "2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 c5 − 8.Bg5 "]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. e6
3. g3( { With this move order, White avoids the line we want to play in the  g3  Queen's Indian, as after }3...b6 4.Bg2 { , there is no pawn }{ to attack on  c4 . } )
3. c5{ This is the way to go. Since White does not have a pawn on  c4 , White cannot meet this move with  d5 . }
4. Bg2
4. cxd4
5. Nxd4
5. d5
6. O-O( 6.c4 { would transpose to the  Benoni Declined  chapter. } )
6. e5
7. Nb3{ This line is actually quite tricky and has been played by numerous top players recently, including Magnus Carlsen against Ding Liren. }( 7.Nf3 Nc6 8.c4 d4 { would also transpose to the  Benoni Declined  chapter. } )
7. Be6{ This is the right way to continue our development. We are going to delay ... Nc6 , as we want to be able to meet  Bg5  with ... Nbd7 . }( { The natural-looking }7...Nc6 { would be inaccurate, as here White has }8.Bg5 Be6 9.Nc3 { , with nagging pressure on our center. } )
8. Bg5
8. Nbd7{ This is the point of delaying the development of the knight. }
