[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) London System 3.Bf4"]
[Black "London System 3.Bf4 − 5.Nbd2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. e6{ We have to play this move to be able to transpose to the Queen's Indian. }
3. Bf4
3. c5( 3...d5 { is also fine, as after }4.e3 c5 { , we transpose. } )
4. e3
4. d5{ I recommend this system, as it keeps things very simple and White will never be able to catch us off guard by capturing the pawn on  c5 . Generally, we will follow up with ... Bd6  and ask White how they are going to deal with the offered bishop trade.    Note that we are delaying ... Nc6 , as in some cases we want to be able to go ... Qc7  followed by ... Nbd7 , to prepare the ... e5  break. White has many different move orders, and often they transpose to the same positions. }
5. Nbd2
5. Qb6( { White's idea is that after }5...Bd6 { , White can play }6.dxc5 Bxc5 { followed by a }{ quick  c2 - c4 , taking advantage of the fact that White has not played  c3  yet and thus winning a tempo. } )
6. c4{ Played by Arjun Erigaisi in a rapid game in 2022. However, the way to meet this move is quite straightforward. }( { After }6.dxc5 Bxc5= { , Black is doing absolutely fine, }{ as we will just continue our development with ... O-O  afterwards. }6...Qxb2 { is possible as well, but there is no reason to go into complications since }6...Bxc5 { gives Black a good game. } )( { A common mistake among lower-rated players is to address the threat on the  b2 -pawn by playing }6.b3 { , but Black is already better after }6...Nc6 7.c3 Nh5 { . } )
6. Nc6{ I recommend not to accept any of White's sacrifices and to just keep it simple. After the trades on  d5  and  c5 , Black gets plenty of active play and a good game. }
