[Black "London System 3.Bf4 − 5.c3 Bd6 6.Nbd2 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. e6{ We have to play this move to be able to transpose to the Queen's Indian. }
3. Bf4
3. c5( 3...d5 { is also fine, as after }4.e3 c5 { , we transpose. } )
4. e3
4. d5{ I recommend this system, as it keeps things very simple and White will never be able to catch us off guard by capturing the pawn on  c5 . Generally, we will follow up with ... Bd6  and ask White how they are going to deal with the offered bishop trade.    Note that we are delaying ... Nc6 , as in some cases we want to be able to go ... Qc7  followed by ... Nbd7 , to prepare the ... e5  break. White has many different move orders, and often they transpose to the same positions. }
5. c3
5. Bd6
6. Nbd2
6. O-O
7. Ne5
7. Qc7
8. Bd3
8. b6{ Preparing ... Ba6  to trade off the light-squared bishop on  d3 , which is one of White's most important attacking pieces. }
9. h4{ This has been played by some strong players recently, including Firouzja and Gukesh. White wants to go  h4 - h5 - h6  so they will always have checkmating ideas towards Black's king. And if we stop White's advance with ... h6 , White will try to open up files towards our king with  g4 - g5 . Fortunately, we have time to organize counterplay. }
9. Ba6
10. Bxa6
10. Nxa6
11. h5
11. h6
12. Qf3
12. cxd4
13. exd4
13. Nc5{ Again, it is this move that solves all of our problems. The knight can always jump to  e4  to stop White from playing  g5  and we can create counterplay on the queenside by going ... b5 - b4 . }
